<heading id="D08B81F11757AB61FC0862979B4B1863" box="[924,1344,1781,1802]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" reason="2">
REMARKS ON 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FBA862979B4B1863" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[1084,1344,1781,1802]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FBA862979B4B1863" box="[1084,1344,1781,1802]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FBA862979ACB1863" box="[1084,1216,1781,1802]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">SIMPLOMYS</emphasis>
ROBUSTUS
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1757AB60FCAE637E9C561D64" blockId="18.[826,1441,1820,1903]" lastBlockId="19.[144,759,198,526]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="641" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1757AB61FCAE637E9A2D185B" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[826,1062,1820,1841]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="18" pageNumber="640" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1757AB61FCAE637E9A2D185B" box="[826,1062,1820,1841]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="640">Simplomys robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rare in the fossil record. Its stratigraphical distribution is restricted to the Ramblian and lowest Aragonian (Lower Miocene). In Spain it is present in the Calatayud–Montalbán basin and in the Vallès–Penedès basin (
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1756AB60FD8664869CAE1F91" author="Agusti J" box="[530,677,228,251]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" refId="ref15715" refString="Agusti J. 1981. Roedores miomorphos del Neogeno de Cataluna. Unpublished D. Phil. Thesis, Universidad de Barcelona." type="book" year="1981">Agustí, 1981</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1756AB60FD2D64869FE81E73" author="Ginsburg L &amp; Morales J &amp; Soria D" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" pagination="629 - 632" refId="ref17684" refString="Ginsburg L, Morales J, Soria D. 1987. Nouvelles faunes de grands Mammiferes d'age Miocene inferieur dans la partie orientale du bassin du Tage (Espagne). Consequences stratigraphiques. Comptes Rendus de l'Academie des Sciences de Paris 305: 629 - 632." type="journal article" year="1987">Ginsburg, Morales &amp; Soria (1987)</bibRefCitation>
cited 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FDBF65669CB21E72" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[555,697,259,281]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FDBF65669CB21E72" box="[555,697,259,281]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Ps. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the locality Valquemado (Tagus basin, local zone Y1). However, in later papers (
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1756AB60FE5D655D9FCD1E1E" author="Alvarez Sierra MA &amp; Daams R &amp; Pelaez-Campomanes P" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" pagination="18 - 21" refId="ref15497" refString="Alvarez Sierra MA, Daams R, Pelaez-Campomanes P. 1994. Synthesis of Late Oligocene / Early Miocene micromammal faunas of the Loranca basin (Province of Cuenca, Spain). In: Fernandez Lopez S, ed. Comunicaciones de las X Jornadas de Paleontologia. Madrid: Sociedad Espanola de Paleontologia, 18 - 21." type="book chapter" year="1994">Álvarez Sierra, Daams &amp; Peláez-Campomanes, 1994</bibRefCitation>
; Morales 
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FDAE65029C791E1E" box="[570,626,351,373]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">et al.</emphasis>
, 1999) this material is referred to as 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FE76651F9C991EF8" authorityName="De Bruijn" authorityYear="1966" box="[482,658,381,402]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Pseudodryomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FE76651F9C991EF8" box="[482,658,381,402]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Pseudodryomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[= 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FD54651C9EEB1EDB" authorityName="García-Paredes &amp; Peláez-Campomanes &amp; Álvarez-Sierra" authorityYear="2009" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FD54651C9EEB1EDB" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Simplomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
?] sp. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FEB865FE9C131EDB" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[300,536,412,433]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FEB865FE9C131EDB" box="[300,536,412,433]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Simplomys robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also present in 
<collectingCountry id="F36B760D1756AB60FF0465D99EF81EBB" box="[144,243,443,465]" name="Portugal" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Portugal</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1756AB60FE9D65D99FBE1EBB" author="Antunes MT" box="[265,437,443,465]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" pagination="301 - 323" refId="ref16160" refString="Antunes MT. 1984. Essai de synthese sur les Mammiferes du Miocene de Portugal. Volume d'hommage au geologue G. Zbyszewski. Paris: Ed. Recherche sur les civilisations, 301 - 323." type="book chapter" year="1984">Antunes, 1984</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="F36B760D1756AB60FD9165D99C5F1EBA" box="[517,596,443,464]" name="France" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">France</collectingCountry>
(e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1756AB60FD3465D99F061E85" author="Aguilar JP &amp; Escarguel G &amp; Michaux J" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" pagination="215 - 230" refId="ref15673" refString="Aguilar JP, Escarguel G, Michaux J. 1999. A succession of Miocene rodent assemblages from fissure fillings in southern France: palaeoenvironmental interpretation and comparison with Spain. Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology 145: 215 - 230." type="journal article" year="1999">
Aguilar 
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FF0465B89EC31E84" box="[144,200,473,495]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">et al.</emphasis>
, 1999
</bibRefCitation>
) (see Supporting Information Appendix S1 for details on localities and references).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1756AB60FF20662A9CD91D34" blockId="19.[180,722,584,638]" box="[180,722,584,606]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FF20662A9CD91D34" authority="(HUGUENEY ET AL., 1978)" baseAuthorityName="Hugueney" baseAuthorityYear="1978" box="[180,722,584,606]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="635" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aljaphi">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FF20662A9F951D36" box="[180,414,584,605]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">SIMPLOMYS ALJAPHI</emphasis>
(HUGUENEY 
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FDAF662E9C8B1D37" box="[571,640,584,605]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">ET AL.</emphasis>
, 1978)
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1756AB60FE0C660A9FE61D14" blockId="19.[180,722,584,638]" box="[408,493,616,638]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
(
<figureCitation id="13472A181756AB60FE34660A9FEE1D14" box="[416,485,616,638]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="13.[144,223,1148,1167]" captionTargetBox="[370,1196,198,1116]" captionTargetId="figure-248@13.[367,1199,195,1118]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 6. Simplomys aljaphi (Hugueney et al., 1978) from Montaigu-le-Blin (modified after Hugueney et al., 1978). A, P4-M3 AC. MB 191 holotype. B, p4-m3 P.O. C, P4 AC. MB 103. D, M1 F.S.L. 97 461. E, m3 AC. MB 706. F, m3 F.S.L. 97 464. Right side specimens underlined. Holotype in italics." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443095/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">FIG. 6</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1756AB60FF0466EC9F231B79" blockId="19.[144,759,654,1043]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FF0466EC9FE11DC9" box="[144,490,654,675]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
Original diagnosis (
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1756AB60FEED66EC9FE11DC9" author="Hugueney M &amp; Collier A &amp; Huin J &amp; Olivier P" box="[377,490,654,675]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" pagination="27 - 45" refId="ref17797" refString="Hugueney M, Collier A, Huin J, Olivier P. 1978. Un gliride nouveau du Miocene de Montaigu-le-Blin (Allier): Pseudodryomys aljaphi nov. sp. (Mammalia, Rodentia). Revue Scientifique du Bourbonnais 1978: 27 - 45." type="journal article" year="1978">Hugueney</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
et al., 
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FDAA66EC9F601DA8" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">1978: 28, translated from French):</emphasis>
‘[
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FE1466CF9C3B1DA8" authorityName="De Bruijn" authorityYear="1966" box="[384,560,685,706]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Pseudodryomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FE1466CF9C3B1DA8" box="[384,560,685,706]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Pseudodryomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
similar in size to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FF0466AE9F0D1D8A" authorityName="De Bruijn" authorityYear="1966" box="[144,262,715,737]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Pseudodryomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ibericus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FF0466AE9F0D1D8A" box="[144,262,715,737]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">P. ibericus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FED666AE9FE41D8A" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[322,495,715,737]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FED666AE9FE41D8A" box="[322,495,715,737]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">P. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, close to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FDC966AE9CD81D8A" authorityName="De Bruijn" authorityYear="1966" box="[605,723,715,737]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Pseudodryomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ibericus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FDC966AE9CD81D8A" box="[605,723,715,737]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">P. ibericus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the evolutionary degree of its M1-2, which also possesses centrolophs and sometimes accessory ridges, but with a protoloph almost parallel to the metaloph, which gives a quite less pointed trigon on the upper molars; this new species on the whole has more simple molars than 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FEE167E69FE11CF2" authorityName="De Bruijn" authorityYear="1966" box="[373,490,899,921]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Pseudodryomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ibericus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FEE167E69FE11CF2" box="[373,490,899,921]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">P. ibericus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with P4 and M3 much more reduced and very simplified. The reduction of the P4 and M3 is not as extreme as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FDD267A39CFB1CBF" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[582,752,960,982]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FDD267A39CFB1CBF" box="[582,752,960,982]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">P. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which, in addition, has upper molars without centrolophs]’.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1756AB60FF0460599FFC1AB4" blockId="19.[144,759,1083,1502]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FF0460599F701B3A" box="[144,379,1083,1104]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Emended diagnosis:</emphasis>
Medium-sized 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FDA360599CBE1B3A" authorityName="García-Paredes &amp; Peláez-Campomanes &amp; Álvarez-Sierra" authorityYear="2009" box="[567,693,1083,1104]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FDA360599CBE1B3A" box="[567,693,1083,1104]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Simplomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The dental pattern of the upper molars is formed by the four main ridges. Centrolophs may be present. Sometimes tiny extra ridges are present inside the trigon. The M1 and M2 show a protoloph almost parallel to the metaloph; both ridges are joined near the lingual border. The dental pattern of m1 and m2 consists of the four main ridges and a well-developed centrolophid. The centrolophid does not exceed the central axis of the occlusal surface. The m1 and m2 also may possess tiny and low extra ridges in variable positions. The premolars and the m3 show the lowest degree of reduction and simplification amongst species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FE9C61AA9F8D1AB7" authority="García-Paredes &amp; Peláez-Campomanes &amp; Álvarez-Sierra, 2009" authorityName="García-Paredes &amp; Peláez-Campomanes &amp; Álvarez-Sierra" authorityYear="2009" box="[264,390,1480,1501]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FE9C61AA9F8D1AB7" box="[264,390,1480,1501]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Simplomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23B57F41756AB60FE0461AB9FFC1AB4" box="[400,503,1481,1502]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1756AB60FF0462679C171806" blockId="19.[144,759,1541,1900]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FF0462679C601970" box="[144,619,1541,1562]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
Differential diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FE0762679C601970" box="[403,619,1541,1562]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aljaphi">Simplomys aljaphi</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FF0462469F4E1953" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[144,325,1572,1593]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FF0462469F4E1953" box="[144,325,1572,1593]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">S. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its less reduced and simplified premolars and m3. When centrolophs are present in the M1 and M2, they extend diagonally into the central valley. The anterior one is always present and longer than the posterior one in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FE6962FD9C6619D9" box="[509,621,1694,1716]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aljaphi">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FE6962FD9C6619D9" box="[509,621,1694,1716]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">S. aljaphi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FF0462DF9F4819B8" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[144,323,1725,1746]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FF0462DF9F4819B8" box="[144,323,1725,1746]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">S. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the centrolophs are closer to being parallel to protoloph and/or metaloph and the posterior one is longer. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FEFE62989C4F1865" box="[362,580,1786,1807]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aljaphi">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FEFE62989C4F1865" box="[362,580,1786,1807]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Simplomys aljaphi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FD4B62999F141844" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FD4B62999F141844" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">S. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having, in general, a more complicated dental pattern in the lower molars that may include tiny and low extra ridges.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1756AB60FCAB64A49B861F90" blockId="19.[806,1421,198,250]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FCAB64A49A101FB1" box="[831,1051,198,219]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aljaphi">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FCAB64A49A101FB1" box="[831,1051,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Simplomys aljaphi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FB2E64A49B341FB1" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[1210,1343,198,219]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FB2E64A49B341FB1" box="[1210,1343,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">S. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its smaller size and its more complicated dental pattern.
</paragraph>
